00:09:59.650 --> 00:10:01.600
What we do, if you want to
integrate with Google Wallets

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:05.435
for digital goods, what you do
is you create a JWT, or a J,

00:10:05.435 --> 00:10:08.470
W, T, which stands for
a JSON Web Token.

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.870
This describes the thing
that you're selling.

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:13.090
I've got an example here
on the screen.

00:10:13.090 --> 00:10:15.610
It's a data structure here that
holds the description of

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:17.700
a digital item being sold.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:20.490
You can see in here, we've got
the issuer, which is the

00:10:20.490 --> 00:10:24.090
person selling the item, the
audience, which is us, Google.

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:27.750
We've got an issued-at time
and an expiration date and

00:10:27.750 --> 00:10:28.670
also a type.

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:30.390
The "type" field there
is important.

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:33.390
It's just "typ." It says
the type of purchase

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:35.160
that is being made.

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:37.640
That purchase is described
in the request

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:39.010
substructure in here.

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:42.850
And in there, you can see the
name, description, price, and

00:10:42.850 --> 00:10:45.860
currency code of what's being
sold, along with an optional

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:49.220
field called "seller data."
Google does not interpret the

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:49.940
seller data.

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:53.210
We simply hold onto it and echo
it back to you later once

00:10:53.210 --> 00:10:55.630
a purchase or a subscription
has been completed.

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:58.260
It's a good place to do your
own record-keeping.

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:00.750
So once you've created the JWT,
basically once you've

00:11:00.750 --> 00:11:03.730
create that data structure and
run it through a JWT library

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:09.310
that will actually JSON encode
it, and base64 encode it, and

00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:11.240
sign in with your secret key.

00:11:11.240 --> 00:11:15.050
Then you need to pass it into
our JavaScript library.

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:17.870
We've tried to keep this
very simple as well.

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:20.280
What you would typically do
here is put your own "Buy"

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:23.010
button on your page,
bind the "Buy"

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:24.620
button to a click handler.

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:27.330
In this case, we've called it
"purchase." And in that

00:11:27.330 --> 00:11:30.040
"purchase" function-- this is
just a JavaScript function--

00:11:30.040 --> 00:11:33.160
you can pass the JWT into
our JavaScript Buy call.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:36.100
Along with the JWT,
you can provide a

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:38.230
success and failure callback.

00:11:38.230 --> 00:11:40.030
These, again, are just
JavaScript functions.

00:11:40.030 --> 00:11:43.790
And they get called when
somebody exits the buy flow.

00:11:43.790 --> 00:11:46.500
Now with subscriptions it's
really, really similar.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:48.470
So if you've already integrated
for items, then

00:11:48.470 --> 00:11:49.930
doing it for a subscription
should be pretty

00:11:49.930 --> 00:11:50.940
straightforward.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:52.860
I've highlighted the
changes in yellow.

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:55.660
The JWT structure is
slightly different.

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:58.650
Instead of being for an item in
the "type" field, it's for

00:11:58.650 --> 00:12:00.320
a subscription instead.

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:02.760
And the contents of the request
substructure are

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:04.290
slightly different as well.

00:12:04.290 --> 00:12:07.120
Instead of having the price and
currency code right there

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:09.680
in the request, we've got
another structure inside of

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:11.480
there that we call
a recurrence.

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:14.990
And in there we've got price,
currency code, and frequency.

00:12:14.990 --> 00:12:17.770
So you can see in this example,
we're charging $4.99

00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:19.510
a month, USD.

